All references to tp.atrace, tp.ctrace, tp.etrace can be removed. These are calls to an internal trace facility that have no effect on the execution of the method.

wrt: wc.setAttribute("org.eclipse.jdt.launching.MAIN_TYPE", "com.bull.eclipse.junit.TestDriver");

TestDriver class referenced MAIN_TYPE is a simple class that extends TestCase and has a single suite() method that constructs a test suite based on a config file.  The class can be replaced by any class that extends TestCase.

Consider the AffixedEditPart extends AbstractBorderItemEditPart as a default way to create side-affixed edit parts. In this case runtime infrastructure installs delegating layout that delegates layouting for AffixedEditPart#getFigure() to the BorderItemLocator. 

The problem is that during the whole lifecycle of the BorderItemLocator it never sets the size of the bordered figure. In particular, consider the gmf generated code: 

/**
* @generated 
* for some side-affixed node
*/
protected NodeFigure createNodePlate() {
     NodeFigure result = new DefaultSizeNodeFigure(getMapMode().DPtoLP(40), getMapMode().DPtoLP(40));
     /*SIC!!!*/ result.getBounds().setSize(result.getPreferredSize());
     return result;
}

In case if the line markered as /*SIC*/ would be removed, the BorderItemLocator will always operate with bounds of width=height=0 and border item will never shown on diagram.

This problem can not be reproduced with side-affixed editparts from Logic example, due to the usage of extended locator class that takes initial size into account. It would be very helpful to have this problem resolved in the default locator implementation.

