New code

//////
        public void resourceChanged( final IResourceChangeEvent event )
        {
            final IResourceDelta delta = event.getDelta();

            synchronized( ProjectFacetsManagerImpl.this.projects )
            {
                for( Iterator itr = ProjectFacetsManagerImpl.this.projects.values().iterator(); 
                     itr.hasNext(); )
                {
                    final FacetedProject fproj = (FacetedProject) itr.next();

                    // handle project deletes

                    final IResourceDelta projectSubDelta 
                    		= delta.findMember( fproj.getProject().getFullPath() );

                    if(projectSubDelta != null 
                    		&& projectSubDelta.getKind() == IResourceDelta.REMOVED){
                    	itr.remove();
                    	continue;
                    }

                    final IResourceDelta subdelta 
                        = delta.findMember( fproj.f.getFullPath() );

                    if( subdelta != null )
                    {
                     	   try
                           {
                               fproj.refresh();
                           }
                           catch( CoreException e )
                           {
                               FacetCorePlugin.log( e );
                           }

                     }
                }
            }
        }


/////

That's not the only reason. For instance it is very desirable that the following always holds true:

IFacetedProject fp1 = ProjectFacetsManager.create( "abc" );
// ... some time passes, a bunch of changes are done, etc.
IFacetedProject fp2 = ProjectFacetsManager.create( "abc" );
assert fp1 == fp2;

Again, part of the reasoning is to align with how the platform handles Project instances. Also, from safe api standpoint, it would be very undesirable to have unmanaged instances of FacetedProject floating around, which would happen if they are "freed".

Caring about identity is never smart. It is smarter to care about equality.
In other words, the following should hold true:

IFacetedProject fp1 = ProjectFacetsManager.create( "abc" );
// ... some time passes, a bunch of changes are done, etc.
IFacetedProject fp2 = ProjectFacetsManager.create( "abc" );
assert fp1.equals(fp2);
